@Node Introduction "Introduction to ConfScan - /X-PoWeR! - Written by KiLLrAvEn/MYSTiC"
                     - - ≠ ≠ ≠ [ iNTRODUCTiON ] ≠ ≠ ≠ - -

   Welcome to ConfScan!

   ConfScan  was  written  during a period of 1 year and has become quite
   a  powerful  program  with  many possibilities and great potential.  I
   have spent a lot of time programming and testing it so I hope you will
   like it and use it with pleasure.

   A little bit of history...

   At first ConfScan was merely meant as a small util that enabled sysops
   to  easily  check  what  was uploaded in all the different conferences
   without  having  to  join them one by one.  The very first version did
   nothing  more  than  that.  That was version 1.0.  It was never really
   released but to a few friends.

   Nowadays ConfScan can perform a much greater task than just displaying
   some  filenames  on  the  screen.  ConfScan can now be used to control
   some  main  parts  of  the  bulletin  board  system Ami-Express.  With
   ConfScan  you  can  scan for new files, view them from within ConfScan
   and you can even Nuke files with ConfScan.  Usage of ConfScan has been
   made as intuitive as possible and should be very easy to use.

   ConfScan  is  an  intelligent program, detecting the options for every
   user  using  ConfScan, not showing options that they don't have access
   for.   ConfScan  also recognizes Ami-X Net conferences that usually do
   not have file bases, as a result these conferences without a file base
   are not shown in the config menu ('CS W').

   ConfScan  comes  with  a  highly user friendly GUi Config program!  No
   more  tooltypes  to fill in by the sysop!  Just start the program from
   the CLi or Workbench and CLiCK the options you want and save'm!

   ConfScan  is  made  in a way that you don't have to repeat information
   that  is  already known is other files or icons.  ConfScan knows where
   to find it and will use it.  But in my opinion that is something every
   program  should  support.   Besides that, if you have any problem with
   ConfScan  you  can  always reach me for support, I am offering support
   for all registered sysops of Ami-Express, FOR FREE!

   But  not only for you, the sysop, ConfScan is a must.  Your users will
   also  appreciate  it  since  ConfScan  allows users to tag their files
   instead  of  flagging them (but they can still flag files if they want
   to  ofcourse)  and  ConfScan  enabled  them  to  download  files  from
   different   conferences  without  having  them  to  jump  through  the
   conferences  by  theirselves.   in  the  near  future, it will also be
   possible  to  download all files from all conferences in one time!  So
   look out for the coming version!

   ConfScan also offers your users a large configurability.  ConfScan has
   a Config Menu built in so they can easily adjust their preferences.

   A seperate Download door enables you to put restrictions on downloads.
   With  the  GUi  Config  program  you can easily exclude conferences or
   nodes from downloading.  You can put accesslevels on nodes/conferences
   or  even  use userlists for download access on nodes/conferences.  And
   all  this  information is again saved by the Config program, so you do
   not have to fill in any tooltypes (GUi Config does that for you).

   if  this  sounds  like  a  useful  program in your ears, check out the
   @{"features" link features} to find out more.  Or at least start the GUi Config.

                                                        @{"-KiLLrAvEn/MYSTiC" link Killraven}

@EndNode

@Node Requirements "What DO you need? - /X-PoWeR! - Written by KiLLrAvEn/MYSTiC"
                   - - - ≠†≠†≠ [ REQUiREMENTS ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   The  requirements can differ a lot since you can setup ConfScan anyway
   you  like,  but  if  you  want to use ConfScan to the fullest you need
   this:

   ∑ @{" Ami-Express BBS " link Ami-X} version 3.38+ (/X 4.x is supported)
   
     YOU NEED VERSiON 3.38 OR HiGHER TO RUN THiS PROGRAM, PLEASE OBTAiN
     THE LATEST VERSiON FROM YOUR DEALER (SEE "AMi-EXPRESS BBS").

   ∑ @{" Clean dir files " link CleanDir}

   For the support of [V]iewing files you need to have in your C: dir
   ∑ DMS
   ∑ LHA
   ∑ UNZiP

   If you want to be able to nuke files with ConfScan you need to have

   ∑ @{" KiLLER " link KiLLER}

   installed on your system.

@EndNode

@Node CleanDir "VERY iMPORTANT! READ THiS! - By KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                 - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ CLEAN DiR FiLES ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   This  may sound obvious, but to get the most out of ConfScan, you need
   to  have  clean  dir files.  So no taglines or any other alien text in
   your dir files.

   There is one exception on the other hand, there is one program you are
   allowed to use to alter your dir file and that is DirStyle by The Bird
   of  TRSi.   Support  for this dirstyler is built in to ConfScan.  This
   was  done  after a request from Sal-One/TRSi.  If you have a dirstyler
   that  you  would like to have support for, contact me and maybe we can
   work something out.

   Nukers on the other hand cause no problems.  You are free to use them,
   even better, there is support for two nukers:  BossNuke and KiLLER.

   "What  can  go  wrong  if I use a dirstyler?" you might wonder.  Well,
   there  is  one thing that can go wrong; file-tagging.  ConfScan uses a
   algorithm  to  recognize  filenames in the dir-file.  But if you use a
   dirstyler  that  puts text where normally filenames are, ConfScan will
   see that text as a filename.

   If  you  still want to use that dirstyler, you can turn of the tagging
   with the Config program (see @{"Configuration" link Configuration}).
@EndNode

@Node Installation "How to get it working - /X-PoWeR! - Written by KiLLrAvEn/MYSTiC"
                    - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ iNSTALLATiON ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   To install ConfScan, simply double-click on the install-ConfScan icon.

   Installation  will  proceed  with  the  C=  installer.   Help has been
   provided  in  the  installer  program,  so  no  need  to  repeat  that
   information in here.

   What can you do with the installer? The installer script will:

   ∑ Allow  you  to  install  the  ConfScan  main  executable  (ConfScan
     itself).  You can choose either for the 68000 or 680x0 version.

   ∑ Allow you to install the ConfScan_DL Download door that  is  needed
     for Ami-Express to recognize any flagged/tagged  files.   This  one
     comes in just one flavour, 68000.

   ∑ Allow you to install the ConfScan_G door which checks if users have
     flagged  files  still  not  downloaded  before they logoff (a small
     patch for the original 'G' door, nothing special).

   ∑ Allow  you to install the help files that come with ConfScan.  Such
     files are needed to give help to users that use ConfScan.  They can
     get  access  to  these  files  by putting a question mark after the
     command (ie.  `N ?').

   ∑ Allow  you to install the fully GUi Configuration program (Config).
     This  program  will  allow  you  to  mold ConfScan to your personal
     needs.   Here you can set all pre-defined preferences, such as ANSi
     support,  show  new  dates  etc.   etc.  But this is also the place
     where  you  can  set  download restrictions and exclude conferences
     from being scanned.  And much more!

   ∑ Allow you to install this guide. You are reading it now.

   ∑ Let  you  choose  as  which  command  you  can to install ConfScan.
     ConfScan  can  act like 3 different commands, `N', `F' and `CS'.  I
     suggest  you install it as all 3 functions, but if you want you can
     skip the `CS' door 'cause it is built-in in `N' also.

   ∑ Let  you  select the place where you want to install ConfScan.  The
     default  destination  is  "DOORS:" but you are free to put it where
     you  want  (the  destination  will  be  put  in  the  command icons
     afterwards).   Remember,  a directory `ConfScan' will be created in
     that directory!

   ∑ Let  you  select  the  name  of  the  command  that the ConfScan_DL
     download  door will be installed under.  I strongly suggest you put
     it under the 'D' cause otherwise users will not be able to download
     anything ;)

   ∑ Let  you select the place where you want to install the Ami-Express
     commands.
     (Default: BBS:Commands/BBSCmd/).

   ∑ Let you set the minimum level required to use any of the ConfScan
     related commands.
     (Default: 20).

   ∑ Let  you  set the priority ConfScan will get when executed (only if
     you  are  an  expert user).  If you are running a multinode system,
     please  set  it  to 0, otherwise users on the other nodes will have
     hindrance  from  it  if  you  give  it +1.  Systems with 1 node can
     easily set it to +1 or +5 for maximum performance.
     (Default: 0).

   ∑ Ask for the directory where you keep your ACP.info.  This is needed
     for the Config program.

   ∑ Start the Config program for you so you can configure ConfScan.

   All  commands will get a stack of 50,000 and will be set to multinode.
   As ConfScan is written in C and ASM, it will be installed as a XiM.
   
   If  you want ConfScan installed under another name than `CS', you will
   have  to  do  it by hand.  But you can still use the installer.  After
   installation,  simply rename the CS.info icon in your BBS:Commands/...
   directory  to  whatever  you  want  (for example, `SCAN').  This will,
   however,  force  you  to rename some of the help files as well (rename
   every file that has ".CS." in it to ".SCAN.").
@EndNode

@Node Configuration "Config - For easy configuration - KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                  - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ CONFiGURATiON ] ≠†≠†≠ - - -

   ConfScan  comes  with an external configuration program called Config.
   It  is  fully  GUi  so  no more stupid textfiles to create or icons to
   fill.   Just  start  the  program  and  away  you  are.  Here are some
   guidelines where you can find some stuff and what it all means.


              ^-[ ACCESS LEVELS ]-^

   Hold Access       ≠ Every user with an access level equal to or higher
                       than  the  value  you enter here, is able to watch
                       the contents of the hold dirs.
                       (Default:  250).

   View Access       ≠ Every  user with an access level >= than the value
                       you  enter  here,  is  able to view files that are
                       shown  in  the  dir  file.   You can specify which
                       filetypes   are  supported  via  the  View  prefs.
                       (Default:  20).

   KiLL Access       ≠ Every  user with an access level >= than the value
                       you  enter  here,  is  able  to  flag/tag files as
                       KiLLER  targets.  This is for usage with the nuker
                       @{"'KiLLER'" link KiLLER}.
                       (Default:  250).

                ^-[ iNTRO FiLE ]-^

   Intro file        ≠ The  filename that you can specify here (either by
                       entering the filename in the text box or selecting
                       it  with 'S') will be the name of the file that is
                       shown at every startup of ConfScan.  At the moment
                       you  can enter no variables (such as time/date and
                       place).
                       (Default:  <none>).

         ^-[ DEFAULT USER PREFERENCES ]-^

   These are the values that are used if an user does not have his or her
   own private configuration for ConfScan.

   ANSi Colours      ≠ This  option  turns the colours on or off when the
                       files  are  showed  in your screen.  You can setup
                       those colours via the `Colours' button.
                       (Default: Off)

   Show Sent-by      ≠ By  default,  ConfScan  will  filter  out any file
                       description  lines  that  start  with  'Sent by:'.
                       They  are  usually not interesting for users.  But
                       with  the  latest File_iD's and SentBy's you don't
                       know what to expect anymore.
                       (Default: Off)

   Show New Dates    ≠ Every time a new date is detected, a little banner
                       will be displayed informing you of the new date.
                       (Default: Off)

   Clear Screen      ≠ After  *every*  prompt, the screen will be cleared
                       if  you  turn  this option on.  This speeds up the
                       display  on  screen  quite  a  bit, esspecially on
                       local nodes, try it.
                       (Default: Off)

   Lines b/files     ≠ Some  users  find  it  usefull  to have a line put
                       between all the files.  This does the trick.
                       (Default: Off)

   Pause b/confs     ≠ This   will   put  a  pause  banner  between  each
                       conference that has got new files.
                       (Default: Off)

   Return b/files    ≠ Some  users  find it usefull to have an empty line
                       between  all  the  files.  If you've got the time,
                       use  it,  it  makes  it  easier  to detect all the
                       different files.
                       (Default: Off)

   One line per file ≠ If  you  turn  this on, just the first line of the
                       file description will be shown.  Very handy if you
                       want to tag a lot of files FAST.
                       (Default: Off)

   Always full desc. ≠ This   will   prevent   file  descriptions  to  be
                       displayed broken on your screen.  Turn this on and
                       from  *every*  file you will always get to see the
                       entire   file   description.   This  mode  can  be
                       overridden with the [P] at the flag-prompt.
                       (Default: Off)

   Future expansion  ≠ Guess what? Not used.

               ^-[ SYSOP PREFS ]-^

   This  is  where you set all the internal preferences ConfScan will use
   while operating.  It more or less controls the engine of ConfScan.

   Copy dirfiles     ≠ With  multiple node systems, this is a must!  This
                       will   first  copy  your  dirfile  to  T:   before
                       searching   it  for  a  file  date.   This  allows
                       multinode support.
                       (Default: Off)

   Callerslog        ≠ Every  time ConfScan is started and this option is
                       activated,  it  will  be logged in the callerslog.
                       (Default: Off)

   Use Percentage    ≠ A  nice feature of ConfScan is, that it is capable
                       of  showing  a  percentage  (%)  on  screen  while
                       searching  the  dirfiles.  If you don't want this,
                       turn this option off.
                       (Default: On)

   Nuker Support     ≠ ConfScan  is  also able to recognize comments made
                       with   nukers.   Currently  supported  nukers  are
                       BossNuke  and  KiLLER.   But any comment placed on
                       the  spot where normally the file-size is, will be
                       seen  as  a nuker comment.  Any nuker comment will
                       be  display  with a dark-blue background and white
                       characters.   If  you  don't  want that to happen,
                       turn this off.
                       (Default: On)

   Allow Tagging     ≠ @{"Tagging" link Tagging}  is  a  thing  of the day, ConfScan had it
                       first!   If,  for some reason, you don't want your
                       users to tag files, turn it off.

                       Another  reason  why  you want to turn this option
                       OFF  is  because you use a @{"dirstyler" link CleanDir} that confuses
                       ConfScan in it's file-recognition algorithm.
                       (Default: On)

           ^-[ iGNORED CONFERENCES ]-^

   Any  conference you put in this listview will NOT be seen by ConfScan.
   That  means  that  it will not scan the conference for new files (CS),
   not will it be shown when the users wants to set his/her config.

   You  can  add  a conference with "Add Conf", a list will appear of all
   your conference and simply click on the one you want to add.

   To remove a conference, select the one you want to remove and click on
   "Del Conf".  Izze simple.

                 ^-[ COLOURS ]-^

   If  you  click  on  the [Colours] button, you will get a new window in
   which you can enter the colours for the file listing.

   The  values  you  can enter are ANSi ESC colour codes, here is a brief
   display of all colours:

             BLACK = 30 - RED    = 31 - GREEN = 32 - YELLOW = 33
             DBLUE = 34 - PURPLE = 35 - LBLUE = 36 - WHiTE  = 0

   Filename          ≠ Colour of the filenames.
                       (Default: 36)

   Status            ≠ Colour of the file status (P = Passed, etc.).
                       (Default: 35)

   File Size         ≠ Size of the file (no, really?).
                       (Default: 33)

   File Date         ≠ Date of the file (no kidding?).
                       (Default: 31)

   Description       ≠ Colour that will be used for the file description.
                       Mind  you  that  this ESC sequence will be sent at
                       the  start  of  the  file description.  That means
                       that  if  there is an ANSi colour code in the file
                       description, the remainder of the file description
                       will  be  in  THAT  colour  code  and not that you
                       specify here.
                       (Default: 0)

                       NOTE:   Although ESC[37m is also the ANSi code for
                       white,  Ami-Express fails to handle this correctly
                       cause  the  local  node  will show RED (while your
                       users  will  actually  have  white).  But by using
                       ESC[0m you can circumvent this problem.

                ^-[ ViEW PREFS ]-^

   This  is  where  you  can specify which filetypes are allowed to view.
   Currently supported filetypes are:

   DMS               ≠ Files  that  have  DMS  as  a file extension.  The
                       action  that  is  performed on these files is "DMS
                       ViEW <filename>".
                       (Default: On)

   LHA               ≠ These  are  files  that  have  LHA  or  LZH  as an
                       extension.   The action performed on such files is
                       "LHA V <filename>".
                       (Default: On)

   Text files        ≠ A whole range of extensions go for this file type:
                       NFO,  NF0,  TXT,  DOC  and  ASC.   These files are
                       simply  shown  to  them.   This  might  be the ONE
                       filetype  you  want  to  turn  off  since the show
                       routine will NOT abort display when it sees binary
                       codes.
                       (Default: On)

   ZiP files         ≠ Files with the extension ZiP will be attacked with
                       an "ZiP -v <filename>" command and the result will
                       be shown on screen.
                       (Default: On)

                 ^-[ SAVE iT! ]-^

   To  save  all your settings, simply click on the [Save & Exit] button.
   To quit without saving, close the window.

      ^-[ WHAT ABOUT THAT OTHER BUTTON? ]-^

   That  button  [ConfScan_DL]  lets  you setup some restrictions for the
   download command.  See the @{"ConfScan_DL guide" link ConfScan_DL} for that!
@EndNode

@Node Features "Features of ConfScan - /X-PoWeR! - Written by KiLLrAvEn/MYSTiC"
                      - - - ≠†≠†≠ [ FEATURES ] ≠†≠†≠ - - -

 ∑ GUi  Config  program that can be started from the CLi or Workbench for
   easy configuration of ConfScan, a first for an /X-Tool!

 ∑ FAST searching with LOW memory consumption! Max. 60Kb per node!

 ∑ ConfScan  can  act  like `N', `F' and it's own `CS'.  So you get three
   programs for the download of one!  8-)

 ∑ ConfScan  can  show  you the full file descriptions always, so no more
   broken file descriptions on your screen.  Fully user configurable.

 ∑ One  of the main features of ConfScan is ofcourse the fact that it can
   scan  multiple  conferences in one time, this is unique!  No other dir
   scanner is able to do that but ConfScan.

 ∑ Another  feature  is  the  file  @{"tagging" link Tagging}.  Although other dir scanners
   provide  this  options  also,  ConfScan was the first to use it and it
   kind of revolutionized the way of tagging/flagging files.

 ∑ Users  can  setup  ConfScan  to  their  own  personal  likings  via  a
   preferences  menu they can call up with the 'W' argument.  But this is
   not  so special anymore.  Maybe the fact that it looks good and has no
   overabundance  of  colours  in  it make it better than the other ones.
   Also,  ConfScan recognizes conferences without a filebase and will not
   even show them to users in the config menu.

 ∑ This is what the users can setup for theirselves:
   ≠ ANSi colour display
   ≠ Line between files
   ≠ Return between files
   ≠ Pause between conferences
   ≠ Show new dates
   ≠ Show sent-by (or not)
   ≠ Always show full descriptions
   ≠ Clear Screen after every prompt
   ≠ Show just the 1st line of a description

 ∑ Like I said above, ConfScan recognizes conferences without a filebase.
   This is done to support Ami-X Net conferences (they usually don't have
   them). You don't have to specify them, ConfScan is 'smart'.

 ∑ Scanning options; ConfScan has them, here you go:

   ≠ Scanning from a certain date
   ≠ Scanning from a number of days back
   ≠ Scanning from the day a user was last on
   ≠ Scanning from [t]oday
   ≠ Scanning in current conference or all conferences
   ≠ Scanning in upload dirs, all dirs or specified dir
   ≠ Scanning in hold dirs (special access-level required)
   ≠ Scanning in selected conferences (user configurable)
   ≠ Scanning with a byte- & filereport afterwards for users with
     [H]old access (f.e. cosysops).
   ≠ Scanning non-stop

 ∑ Flagging  from  ALL  conferences is possible, ConfScan will keep track
   itself  of all the files flagged and via the Download door, /X will be
   informed about them (i.o.w.  they will be flagged).

 ∑ The  special  download  door  does  more  then just flag files for the
   users.  It can automatically join the next conference where files were
   flagged  by  the user.  This can be done straight away when they start
   the download command in a conference where they have selected no files
   or right after the downloading of files of that conference.

   NOTE!       In  the near future, ConfScan will be able to send all the
   ~~~~~       files  to  the  users  in  ONE  time.  This saves time and
               trouble  for your users as well as for your board, it will
               be  less  busy. 

 ∑ With  @{"KiLLER" link KiLLER} installed, you can nuke files from within ConfScan.  Most
   likely  you  will find a beta version of KiLLER inside and you will be
   able  to  test it.  As soon as I've finished coding it, I will release
   it  and  make  sure  you  can  still keep using it in cooperation with
   ConfScan as well as a stand-alone program.

   ALSO READ THE @{" HiSTORY " link History} iN THiS GUiDE FOR MORE iNFO ABOUT THESE
   FEATURES!

@EndNode

@Node Usage "Usage by users (that includes you) - /X-PoWeR! - Written by KiLLrAvEn/MYSTiC"
                       - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ USAGE ] ≠†≠†≠ - - -

   ConfScan  is  very  easy  to  use, despite of it's army of options ;-)
   ConfScan comes with a set of very clear help files that your users can
   call  in for help with '<command> ?'.  This goes for 'N', 'F', 'G' and
   'CS'.   Here are they in plain ASCII.  Feel free to change them if you
   want  to.   To  get  a  full  view  of all recognized command, see the
   @{"ALL COMMAND LIST" link SysopCommands}.

   All the help is put into separate files for your convenience.  This is
   done  to  support  multiple screentypes (so you can have separate help
   files  for  every  screentype  (=  language)).  They are called:

                      N  - Command   : ConfScan.N.Help.TXT
                      F  - Command   : ConfScan.F.Help.TXT
                      G  - Command   : ConfScan.G.Help.TXT
                      CS - Command   : ConfScan.CS.Help.TXT

                       In that order, their contents are:

                         ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

                              ConfScan User Help 
 
  N -x     Files from x days back        Extra options:
  N <date> Files from <date> and on      ≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠
  N S U    Files since last logon        ∑ Add 'NS' for non stop display
  N T U    Files since today             ∑ Use CTRL-C to break program
  N S G    Files since last logon        ∑ Enter 'N W' for to edit your own
           from all conf's (Global)        personal environment settings.
 
                              Environment Options
 
  ∑ Select global conferences            ∑ Put lines between files on screen
  ∑ Usage of ANSI colours in list        ∑ Put return between files on screen
  ∑ Leave out sent-by's                  ∑ Pause between conferences (only used
  ∑ Display new date banner                when you scan globally)
  ∑ Clear the screen after prompt        ∑ Display only first line of descr.
 
  ∑ Show Full Descriptions is an option that will make sure you will always
    get to see the full description of a file, and never will the description
    of a file be broken on your screen. It is not the opposite of 'one line'!

                          ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

                               ConfScan User Help
 
  F        Pop up 'f' menu               Extra options:
  F <#>    Files from dir <#>            ≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠
  F U      Files from upload dir         ∑ Add 'NS' for non stop display
  F A      Files from all dirs           ∑ Use CTRL-C to break program
  F H      Files from hold dir           ∑ Enter 'F W' for to edit your own
           (access required)               personal environment settings.
 
                              Environment Options
 
  ∑ Select global conferences            ∑ Put lines between files on screen
  ∑ Usage of ANSI colours in list        ∑ Put return between files on screen
  ∑ Leave out sent-by's                  ∑ Pause between conferences (only used
  ∑ Display new date banner                when you scan globally)
  ∑ Clear the screen after prompt        ∑ Display only first line of descr.
 
  ∑ Show Full Descriptions is an option that will make sure you will always
    get to see the full description of a file, and never will the description
    of a file be broken on your screen. It is not the opposite of 'one line'!

                          ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

                               ConfScan User Help
 
  CS -x     Files from x days back       Extra options:
  CS <date> Files from <date> and on     ≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠
  CS A      Files from all dirs          ∑ Add 'NS' for non stop display
  CS T      Files since today            ∑ Use CTRL-C to break program
  CS <#>    Files from dir <#>           ∑ Enter 'CS W' for to edit your own
                                           personal environment settings.
  CS scans globally for new files in     ∑ Add '+' for a byte-report
  the upload dir since last logon          (access required)
  unless specified different (above).
 
                              Environment Options
 
  ∑ Select global conferences            ∑ Put lines between files on screen
  ∑ Usage of ANSI colours in list        ∑ Put return between files on screen
  ∑ Leave out sent-by's                  ∑ Pause between conferences (only used
  ∑ Display new date banner                when you scan globally)
  ∑ Clear the screen after prompt        ∑ Display only first line of descr.
 
  ∑ Show Full Descriptions is an option that will make sure you will always
    get to see the full description of a file, and never will the description
    of a file be broken on your screen. It is not the opposite of 'one line'!

                          ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

                          ConfScan Goodbye Explanation
 
   Theory  Your sysop has installed ConfScan for scanning the dirfiles,
           and ConfScan stores your flagged files in a different matter
           then Ami-Express does (because ConfScan can remember flagged
           files from multiple conferences and /X can't). This also asks
           for a different 'G' command, this is it!
 
           This new commands does the same as the internal one, with a
           few differences:
 
           ^ Ability to start downloading from 'G'
           ^ Ability to view your remaining flagged files
           ^ Ability to remove your remaining flagged files
 
 Practice  Once notified that you have remaining files, your options are:
 
           [G] ^ Goodbye, let me out!             To force ConfScan_G to
           [L] ^ List the remaining files         just log off, enter a
           [D] ^ Download remaining files         '!' after the G ('G !').
           [R] ^ Remove them & log off
           [Q] ^ Quit, back to /X prompt          (c) '94 KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC

                          ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

   SEE ALSO: @{"More options" link More}

@EndNode

@Node Future "Possible Future improvements - /X-PoWeR! - KiLLrAvEn/MYSTiC"
                - - - ≠†≠†≠ [ FUTURE iMPROVEMENTS ] ≠†≠†≠ - - -

 ∑ Downloading  ALL  files  from  ALL  conferences  in ONE time.  This is
   possible now thanks to the help of Joe Hodge (thanks Joe!).  Make sure
   you  are  a  registered  sysop,  or  else you want be able to run that
   version of ConfScan!  It will require /X 3.38+.

 ∑ Improved  file  tagging,  it can be annoying sometimes that you cannot
   reach a file that is still on screen.  I will have to look into that.

 ∑ 'A' command to alter/remove flagged files (multiple conferences ofcoz).

 ∑ 'Z'  command  to  search  in  multiple  conferences  and with ConfScan
   interface.

   Anyway,  if  you  have  suggestions,  make  sure  to  drop me a line at
   Channel-X or at one of the other MYSTiC boards (in Holland preferably,
   that's where  I  am most).  By the way, you don't need to have a
   suggestion to call  the MYSTiC boards, you're welcome at any time, open
   24 hours a day and at your service!

   Let me know what you think and what YOU think needs improvement!

