@Node Errors "What have you done wrong? - /X-PoWeR! - Written by KiLLrAvEn/MYSTiC"
              - - - ≠†≠†≠ [ POSSiBLE ERROR MESSAGES ] ≠†≠†≠ - - -

   Since  nobody  is perfect, there is a slight chance an error may occur,
   there are only a few possible errors, so here they are:

   ≠ "Couldn't allocate memory! Too little memory?"

     Do you have enough memory free to run ConfScan?  The program uses about
     36Kb  of memory (largest block in once is 32Kb for copying files).  The
     best  thing  you can do is reset and try again.  If it still fails, you
     better  buy  a  memory  expansion...  If you have enough memory and you
     still get this error, then please contact me.

   ≠ "Couldn't open temporary file for output! Too little memory?"

     ConfScan  uses a temporary file to store the files which will be showed
     to  you  later,  this  temp  file  is in the T:  directory, do you have
     enough  memory  left?   If your file-listings are really big, this file
     can  be  become  quite large (if you have masses of new warez every day
     (ofcourse  you  have  :-)).  Maybe the file is still present in T:  and
     this  MiGHT  cause  the problem, check the T:  directory...  else reset
     and try again.

   ≠ "Couldn't open file: <name>"

     For  some reason, ConfScan was not able to open the file <name>.  Maybe
     it  was  in  use by another program?  Best thing to do is reset and try
     again.   Another  possibility  is that you have not reserved some Ami-X
     Net- mail area's and ConfScan tries to open a dir file...

   ≠ "Couldn't open icon.library!"

     If  this  happens,  you better install the icon.libary, but this cannot
     happen, 'cause /X 3.xx uses it also, so if the icon.library is missing,
     Ami-X will not startup :-).

   ≠ "Error reading from input file during filecopy!"

     It  seems that something went wrong while reading the input file during
     a  file  copy.  File copies only occur while scanning and when you exit
     the config menu.  Reset and try again.

   ≠ "Error writing to output file during filecopy!"

     Something  went  wrong  while  writing to the output file during a file
     copy.  This can only happen while scanning and when you exit the config
     menu.  Reset and try again.

   ≠ "Couldn't open your config file!"

     For  some  reason ConfScan was not able to create your own config file!
     This should always be possible, better reset and try again.

   Well,  that's  all  the  errors  ConfScan can create.  If you don't get
   ConfScan working on your system, just @{"give a me call" link Killraven} and i'll make sure
   it will work!

@EndNode

@Node Tagging "Tagging, the new way of flagging! - © KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                  - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ TAGGiNG OF FiLES ] ≠†≠†≠ - - -

   Instead of having to type the filenames (or paste them with PowerSnap)
   users  (and  you) can walk over the filenames with the cursor keys and
   select them with spacebar or the '0'.

   The  idea  comes from some PC terminal programs (and not BBS programs!)
   that  allow  their  users to let them 'walk' over the files that are on
   the screen and with one simple touch of the keyboard the file is marked
   as  'flagged'  (or  tagged in this case).  I have implemented this cool
   method in my door! ConfScan was the FiRST to use this method. 

   If  the  user  wishes  to  TAG his files a small bar will appear on the
   first  filename  that  is  on the screen after the last 'more' shown on
   screen.   With  the cursor keys on the numeric keypad the user can move
   up  and  down over the filenames.  With the `0' the user can select and
   deselect  a  file.   A selected file can be recognized at the `*' being
   after the filename.

   Flagging  and tagging can be used through each other, it doesn't matter
   if  you  flag first and then tag, it will work.  You might wonder if it
   still works when the users has no colours on screen (no ANSi).  Yes, it
   works, besides the bar there will also be a '<' sign after the filename
   to point out the current filename.

   This method works ofcourse with all ConfScan imitations (N, F and CS).

   If  you  also are an /X Coder and you want to know more about how I did
   it, just contact me at Channel-X and I will help you further.

               ≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠
               ATTENTiON! ATTENTiON! ATTENTiON! ATTENTiON!
               ≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠≠

   Before  you  all  start screaming and yellin' that there is a bug in my
   program,  you  can  tag  files that are displayed since the last 'more'
   line  (or from the beginning if there was no 'more').  This is done for
   programmer's  simplicity  ;) Maybe in the future it will be possible to
   tag  all  files that are on screen, but that is more difficult than you
   might think (multiple conferences on one screen and so forth).
@EndNode

@Node More "Gimme more! Gimme more! - By KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                  - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ MORE OF CONFSCAN ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   All the help is put into separate files for your convenience.  This is
   done  to  support  multiple screentypes (so you can have separate help
   files  for  every  screentype  (=  language)).   Also, because you can
   determine  access  levels  for  each  action,  separate help files are
   needed.  So here they are:

   ConfScan.More_General.Help.TXT ^ General Help, available to all
   ConfScan.More_KiLLiNG.Help.TXT ^ Help for KiLLING of files
   ConfScan.More_Tagging.Help.TXT ^ Help for Tagging files
   ConfScan.More_Viewing.Help.TXT ^ Help for [V]iewing files

                       In that order, their contents are:

                         ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

                              MORE ABOUT CONFSCAN
 
     [P] ^ Show a full page of files     [A] ^ Non Stop ALL conferences
     [F] ^ Flag files                    [N] ^ Non Stop CURRENT conference
     [C] ^ Clear Screen                  [S] ^ Skip current conference
     [Q] ^ Quit ConfScan                 [D] ^ Start downloading

                         ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

                                 KiLLiNG FiLES 
 
  [K] ^ KiLL FiLES
 
        Either in Tag mode or at the prompt. With 'K' you can select files
        that need to be KiLLED later on with KiLLER. The colour of the bar
        will change if you are in tag mode.
 
  [!] ^ Start KiLLER (you will not return to ConfScan afterwards).

                         ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

                          TAGGiNG FiLES WiTH CONFSCAN
 
  [T] ^ Tag files
 
        Use cursor keys to move the bar over the screen. Press space to
        select or deselect a file. An asterisk (*) will appear after it's
        name meaning it is selected and the colour of the bar will change.

                         ^-^-^-^-[ B R E A K ]-^-^-^-^

                                 ViEWiNG FiLES
 
  [V] ^ View Files
 
        Either at the prompt or when you are tagging, with 'V' you will
        get to view that file.
 
        Supported file types: DMS ^ Disk Masher  (Amiga Disk Archives)
                              ZIP ^ Zip          (msdos File Archives)
                              LHA ^ LhA(rc)      (Amiga File Archives)
                              TXT/DOC/NFO/NF0    (Text files)

@EndNode

@Node Important "Update Information - © 1994 KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ UPDATE iNFORMATiON ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   Congratulations.    You've   found  ConfScan  2.6.06  of  ConfScan,  a
   radically faster version of the ConfScan series.  It has a totally new
   search  routine  that makes it possible to find files within 1 second!
   If  you  were a previous user of ConfScan 2.x, you will most certainly
   notice the difference, esspecially with large dir-files.

   The  original  package still contains the old 2.6 version as they were
   spread on all systems world-wide.  However, this archive also contains
   a  file  called  "Beta_Version.LHA"  and  there you can find the 68000
   version  of  the  version  with the improved search-routine.  There is
   only  an  68000 version.  Once installed with the Installer script you
   can simply copy that version over the installed version.

   IMPORTANT! My internet address has changed: klr@xs4all.nl !

   I  am  working  on a new version (3.0) that will be totally different,
   but  due to circumstances beyond my control this may take a while, but
   you can count on a new version.

   Until then... KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC (Sun Feb  5 15:57:26 1995)

                - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ UPDATE iNFORMATiON ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   Welcome  to  version  2.6  of  ConfScan.  This is just an intermediate
   release,  to  fix  the problem with Ami-Express 4.xx.  I didn't expect
   this  version  of  Ami-Express to be released this soon.  My apologies
   for the error I made (both in judgement as in programming).

   A  few  days  ago  a  saw  a patch of ConfScan going around fixing the
   problem  with  /X  4.x, but the patcher (I don't know who did it and I
   don't care, really) also made it a 4.x door ONLY.  Now that isn't what
   I  had  in  mind!   I know that the patcher couldn't do anything else,
   because it was programmed that way (to check for just 1 version).

   Anyway,  like  I said before, this version wasn't to be released until
   some  other options were build in, but it appears that there is a need
   for  a  fixed  version (I figured that if you wanted a new version you
   would  call  one  of  the MYSTiC boards, there you could get a patched
   version).  So here it is!

   A small overview of all changes since 2.5(.60):
   
   ∑ Flagged  files  from  users  are now saved to a special directory in
     the  ConfScan  directory  (.../Users/). This enables users to safely
     log off and download the files at a later time. Several sysops asked
     for this option.

   ∑ New ConfScan_DL door to read the new structure that ConfScan uses to
     store  the  files.  It also has got a better look and some bugs were
     fixed: ≠ Non-relative Conference jumping now goes fine
            ≠ Files  entered  after  the  'D' command are now flagged and
              recognized  (previously  ConfScan_DL  would inform you that
              there  were no files in the current conference although you
              had just flagged them with the 'D' command).

     New option: ≠ If  you  add '-r' as the first argument after 'D', you
                   will  be  asked  if  you  want to delete (remove) your
                   remaining  files.  This  is  just  a small work-around
                   until my 'A' command is finished.

     Important : To get this working, ConfScan_DL needs to know where you
                 have  stored ConfScan. If you install it with the script
                 there  is  no problem. But if you have already installed
                 it, add the tooltype 'CS_Location=<path>' to your D.info
                 or else it will fail.

   ∑ New Config menu layout and smarter interpretation of the menu.
     If  you  call  the config menu with 'N' or 'F' you will get the menu
     with  environmental  options  first  instead of the menu with the CS
     options (as it was before this release).

   ∑ New  ConfScan_G  command with a LOT more options.  Help is available
     via  'G ?'  (the file is called ConfScan.G.Help.TXT).

     New options involve: ≠ View the remaining files
                          ≠ Remove the remaining files & log off
                          ≠ Download the remaining files

     If  you enter a '!' after the 'G' command, you will force it to just
     shut up and log off 8-)

     Important : To get this working, ConfScan_G needs  to know where you
                 have  stored ConfScan. If you install it with the script
                 there  is  no problem. But if you have already installed
                 it, add the tooltype 'CS_Location=<path>' to your G.info
                 or else it will fail.

   ∑ Quite  a  lot of bugfixes, for a more complete description check the
     @{"history" link History} part, but here are the main points:
     ≠ ConfScan now works fine from any dir, not just the BBSCmd/ dir.
     ≠ Hold access problem fixed (shame shame).
     ≠ Better error information/detection.
     ≠ A percentage is now shown when a dirfile is being copied.
     ≠ Clear Screen works better.
     ≠ Pause between conferences now works like it should work.
     ≠ Dirfiles if size 0 are handled correctly (skipped :) ).
     ≠ The RELATIVE_CONFERENCES bug is fixed. Non-relative conferences
       are now supported.

   ∑ I  wrote  shorter  and  better  help files for the users. They don't
     need  (nor  are  they  interested  in) long textfiles explaining the
     theory  behind  ConfScan.  Please use these instead of the old ones.

   Well,  that's  it  for  now.   Remember,  this is just an intermediate
   release.   The  next  release  (3.0?)  will most likely have a new GUI
   Config and the ability to set up your own set of command's that can be
   called  from  within  ConfScan.  Like I said before in the Guide, I am
   interested in your suggestions, so contact me if you have some!
   
   I would like to take this oppertunity to thank all the people who made
   suggestions  for  ConfScan,  and  in  particulair  Zed,  he's  a great
   beta-tester,  I could need more of his kind!  Thanks man, you are very
   thourough and persistant :-)
   
   Further  more, school has begun again, so my other internet account is
   also  active  again:   robertke@htsa.hva.nl  (yes,  my  first  name is
   Robert). Write me if you feel bored or anything :-) Or you can find me
   on IRC at #Rave or #Amiga under Killraven.

   Goodbye & I hope you enjoy ConfScan!
   
   (Thu Aug 25 14:45:38 1994  -  Kewl,  one  year  exactly  after the 1st
    release!)

@EndNode

@Node ConfScan_DL "Guide to ConfScan_DL - © 1994 KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"

                           Small Guide to ConfScan_DL
                   for AmiExpress BBS together with ConfScan

                            Program version: 2.6.02
                Compilation Date/Time: Thu Aug 25 14:54:47 1994

                           © 1994 by KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC

                       ...part of the ConfScan Package...

                              @{"    Introduction    " link DL_intro}

                              @{"       Usage        " link DL_Usage}

                              @{"    Configuration   " link DL_Configuration}

                              @{"      History       " link DL_History}
@EndNode

@Node DL_intro "introduction to ConfScan_DL - © 1994 KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                    - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ iNTRODUCTiON ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   ConfScan_DL  plays  a very important role inside the ConfScan package.
   it  is  the  link  between all the flagged files and Ami-Express.  You
   MUST install ConfScan_DL if you want to let users download files.  But
   that's not all.

   It  is  great  ofcourse  that  you  now  can  flag files from multiple
   conferences,  but what happens if you want to download them?  Nothing!
   Ami-Express  is not capable to let users download files from different
   conferences  at  once,  thus  I created ConfScan_DL.  ConfScan_DL lets
   users  download files from multiple_conferences.  Unfortunately not at
   once, but it is a great improvement compared to nothing 8-)

   What  ConfScan_DL  does,  is flag the files for the conference that an
   user  is in.  ConfScan_DL checks if there were files selected from the
   current  conference  and  if there are files, they will be flagged and
   the internal download command will be started.

   Besides  flagging the files, ConfScan_DL can automatically jump to the
   next conference where files are selected from.  This can be done right
   after the download or (when there are no files selected in the current
   conference)  straight  away.  Users can always ask for a list with all
   the files they selected.

   But  that  is  not  all!  Many sysops already have another command put
   under  their  'D'.  That makes it impossible to install ConfScan_DL as
   well  under  the  'D'  command.   But  I  found  out  that these doors
   generally  do  the same thing:  check if the user may download or not.
   There  are  lots  of varieties, node checkers, conference checkers and
   even user checkers.  Well, ConfScan_DL has that built in!

   With  ConfScan_DL you can exclude a node, a conference or even an user
   from downloading.  This is done with a few tooltypes in the icon.  You
   can  even  create  a list of people that actually CAN download in that
   conference  or on that node, so anybody who is not in that list cannot
   download.
@EndNode

@Node DL_Usage "How to use ConfScan_DL - © 1994 KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                                 ^-[ USAGE ]-^

   I've  done  my  best  to  make  the  usage  of the DL door as easy and
   convinient  as  possible.   If  a user has not used ConfScan, the user
   will never even know the DL door is being used.

   What  does the user see then?  Well, let's assume an user has selected
   five  files,  1 in conference 1, 2 in conference 2 and 2 in conference
   4.   The  user is in conference 3 and wants to download (thus executes
   the 'D' command).  This is what will happen:

   ∑ ConfScan_DL will check wether downloads on this node are legal.
     If they are not, ConfScan_DL will not allow downloads and will show
     a text file or a brief message.

   ∑ ConfScan_DL will check wether downloads in this conference are legal.
     If they are not, ConfScan_DL will not allow downloads and will show
     a text file or a brief message.

   ∑ ConfScan_DL will check if the user is allowed to download at all.
     If he is excluded from downloading in general (this can be done with
     ConfScan_DL) than that user will either see a brief message telling
     him to sod off or a textfile you can create.

   At  this  point  the  user is allowed to download and ConfScan_DL will
   check  for  files.  If it finds files it will say so, but in this case
   it will say:

  ConfScan v2.6 Download File Checker - (c) Copyright 1994 by KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC

       Files flagged for this conference:   0    Skipped alien files:  5

        Your remaining files have been saved. You can logoff safely and
                 continue downloading another time if you like.

      Would you like to see the list of still remaining files? [Y/n]


   So  ConfScan_DL  does  notice  that  there  are  other  files flagged,
   otherwise  it  will  not ask the user that last question.  Suppose the
   user says "YES"...


                     Files remaining in other conferences:
                     `-----------------------------------'
                      TRP-YZ2.DMS       in Conference   1
                      CATFIX12.LHA      in Conference   2
                      MDBLC004.LHA      in Conference   2
                      AXFUNREG.DMS      in Conference   4
                      BILL&TED.RUL      in Conference   5

    Automatically join the next conference with remaining files? [Y/n]


   The  last question offers the user to automatically jump (join) to the
   next conference where files are flagged.  If the user want so, he will
   be jumped to the next conference (with the installed 'J' command).

   There,  the  user can (and unfortunatelly must) select the 'D' command
   again.  Then he will see:

  ConfScan v2.6 Download File Checker - (c) Copyright 1994 by KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC

       Files flagged for this conference:   1    Skipped alien files:   4

        Your remaining files have been saved. You can logoff safely and
                 continue downloading another time if you like.

      Would you like to see the list of still remaining files? [Y/n]

   Well,  after  that  it  will be the same as shown above, but after the
   download,  ConfScan_DL  will  jump  right  away to the next conference
   where files were flagged (if the user wanted to ofcourse).

   This  will  be  repeated  for  every  conference where files have been
   flagged (or tagged).

                 ^-[ HOW TO GET RiD OF SAVED FLAGGED FiLES ]-^

   Sometimes  it  is desired to get rid of all those saved flagged files.
   Normally  you  would  do  that  with  the  'A' command, but /X doesn't
   recognize  the  ConfScan  files.  So to work around this problem, I've
   built in this option in the 'D' command.

   If  the  first  argument after the 'D' command is '-r', a procedure to
   remove  the flagged files will be started.  I.e.  'D -r' will give you
   this:

               įĪ≤ ConfScan_DL - Remove Personal Saved Files ≤Īį

        Are you sure you want to remove your saved flagged files? [y/N]

   If you are sure, press 'Y' and you will get either

                         Removed your personal file...

   or, when it fails to remove it (for some dark reason):

                      ERROR! FAiLED TO REMOVE YOUR FiLE!

   If you want to remove files that are not there, you will get to see

           You have no personal ConfScan file. Nothing to be removed.

   I think of everything, don't I? 8-)

@EndNode

@Node DL_Configuration "Configuration for ConfScan_DL - © 1994 KiLLraVen/MYSTiC"
                            ^-[ CONFiGURATiON ]-^

   ConfScan_DL  can be configured with the external configuration program
   Config. You can install it with the Installer script.

               ^-[ CONFSCAN_DL ]-^

   The  ConfScan_DL  part  of  the  Config program can be reached via the
   [ConfScan_DL] button in the main screen.  A new window will appear.

   The  "ConfScan_DL  Preferences  window 1" is divided into three parts;
   Node Restrictions, Baud Restrictions and Conference Restrictions.

                        .---------------------------.
       [ Graphical ]    |-----------+---------------|
                        |  NODE     |  CONF    | T  |
        [ Display ]     |  RESTR.   |  RESTR.  | E  |
                        |           |          | X  |
                        |           |          | T  |
            ;-)         |           |          |    |
                        +-----------+----------|    |
                        | BAUD RESTRiCTiONS    |    |
                        `---------------------------'

   Every  time  a  user  wants  to  download, but you have restricted the
   download  for  that  user, the user will get to see a (brief) message.
   This  can  either  be  an internal message or a file that you specify.
   This can be specified PER type of restriction.

   The way you can specify this is universal to all type of restrictions:

   o Internal message
   o Show file

   I think it speaks for itself.

            ^-[ NODE RESTRiCTiONS ]-^

   The  cycle  gadget  at the top of the window lets you walk through all
   your  available  nodes.  Shift-Click to go one back. You might want to
   install Cycle-To-Menu, it's a very nifty and handy tool ;)

          ^-[ CONFERENCE RESTRiCTiON ]-^

   With  the cycle gadget at the top of the window you can (just like the
   nodes)  switch  between conferences. Because some boards have a LOT of
   conferences,  the  'S'  button allows you to select the conference you
   want more easily than the cycle gadget might.

               ^-[ RESTRiCTiONS ]-^

   Both  types  of  restrictions  can have the same sort of restrictions,
   therefore,  the  following  explanation  are valid for either Node and
   Conference restrictions. The explanation will talk about node, but you
   can fill in Conference at any time.

   No restrictions   ≠ If   you   set  the  node's  status  to  this,  no
                       restriction will rest upon this node.  Downloading
                       from this node will be no problem (unless you have
                       a baud restriction).
                       (Default)

   No Downloads      ≠ Downloading  from  that  node  will  be impossible
                       unless  you  give  an  user  special  access  (see
                       further on).

   Accesslevel       ≠ Only users with access level <x> or higher will be
                       able  to  download  from  this node.  If you don't
                       specify  the  access  level  (in the string gadget
                       behind  it),  the  access  level  will  be  0  and
                       everybody will be able to download.

   User list         ≠ Only users that are present in an user list (ASCII
                       format)  are  able to download from this node.  If
                       an  user is not found (or the file does not exist)
                       the  user  can  NOT  download.   You  can  enter a
                       filename in the string gadget beneath it or select
                       a file with the [Select] button.

                       The  user list must consists of an ASCII file that
                       is built up like this:

                       [BOF]
                       Tycoon/MYSTiC
                       KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC
                       ArCaDe/MYSTiC
                       etc.
                       etc.
                       [EOF]

             ^-[ BAUD RESTRiCTiON ]-^

   Although  this  part  of the Config program looks to be separated from
   the  Node  restrictions,  this  part will react to changes made in the
   node  cycle gadget. In other words, any baud restrictions are made for
   the currently visible node in the cycle gadget.

   No restriction    ≠ All baud rates are allowed to download.
                       (Default)

   Minimum baud      ≠ This  is  the minimum baud required for an user to
                       be able download.

                ^-[ SAVE PREFS ]-^

   The  ConfScan_DL  preferences  need  to  be  saved separately from the
   ConfScan  preferences (well, not neccessarily but I programmed it this
   way ;) ). Therefore save them from this window.

   ConfScan_DL  preferences  will  be  saved in the Download command icon
   (most  likely the D icon). The preferences will also be read from this
   icon.

                ^-[ MORE PREFS ]-^

   Yes, there is more, see the next section.

                ^-[ MAiN PREFS ]-^

   This will take you back to the first window.

   The  ConfScan_DL  icon  can  be  TOTALLY  configured  with  the Config
   program, so use it to configure what you want.

   For  you tooltype freaks out there, here is an explanation what Config
   will save...

   There  are  8  tooltypes for ConfScan_DL, but with these tooltypes you
   can achieve a lot!  Here they are, followed by a brief explanation.

   ∑ NODE.x      = "NO" / Access level / Filename (with path)
   ∑ NODE.x.FAiL = iNTERNAL / Filename (with path)

   ∑ CONF.x      = "NO" / Access level / Filename (with path)
   ∑ CONF.x.FAiL = iNTERNAL / Filename (with path)

   ∑ USER.x      = ALWAYS/NEVER (where x is the slotnumber of the user)
   ∑ USER.x.FAiL = iNTERNAL / Filename (with path)

   ∑ AREA.name      = ALWAYS/NEVER (where name is the area name of the user)
   ∑ AREA.name.FiLE = iNTERNAL / Filename (with path)

   First of all, x stands for a number.  So if you want to exclude node 3
   from  downloading,  enter  NODE.3=NO  in  the  icon.   Or  if you want
   conference  10  to  be  a  conference where users cannot download, you
   enter CONF.10=NO in the icon.

   After  NODE.x  or CONF.x you can enter 3 things.  You can either enter
   "NO", an access level or a filename.  If you enter NO downloading from
   that node or conference will be impossible, NOBODY can download.

   If  you  enter  an  access  level, that means that downloading is only
   allowed  when the access level of the user is EQUAL OR HiGHER THAN the
   level you enter.  If his level is too low, than he can't download from
   that node/conference.

   If you enter a filename, ConfScan_DL will open that file and checks if
   that  file  holds  the  handle  of the user.  If it does, the user can
   download, otherwise they will be disappointed.  The file must be build
   up like this:

   ---> CUT <---

   KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC          (ofcourse without the spaces in front of it)
   EMPiRE/MYSTiC
   Pharaoh/SR
   Muad'Dib/5D

   ---> CUT <---

   The  search  routine  is  case insensitive, so don't worry about that.
   The file can be placed anywhere because you have to enter the complete
   path and filename after the NODE.x or CONF.x tooltype.


   Ofcourse  it  is  possible to you want certain users to never download
   (again) on your board or that you want certain users always to be able
   to  download.   This  can be achieved with the USER.x tooltype.  The x
   stands  for the number of the user in your user.data (his slotnumber).
   After  that  you  can either enter NEVER (no download for this guy) or
   ALWAYS (downloading will be no problem).

   The  same  goes  for users with a certain AREA NAME.  This way you can
   prevent  NEW users from downloading at all or any other range of users
   with a particulair AREA NAME (the F option in the user editor).


   Now, when ConfScan_DL sees that an user is not allowed to download, it
   will display a message.  This can be either an internal one or one you
   made  for him :). If you enter iNTERNAL after NODE.x.FAiL, CONF.x.FAiL
   or USER.x.FAiL, the internal message will be send:

                    -----[ NO DOWNLOADiNG ON THiS NODE! ]-----

                    -----[ NO DOWNLOADiNG iN THiS CONF! ]-----

                    -----[ NO DOWNLOADiNG FOR YOU DUDE! ]-----

                    -----[ NO DOWNLOADiNG FOR YOU GEEK! ]-----

                    -----[ NO DOWNLOADiNG AT xxxx BAUD! ]-----
                    -----[ MiNiMAL REQUiRED: xxxx BAUD! ]-----

                                       8-)

   ...or  you  can enter a filename after the .FiLE and that file will be
   shown instead, it's just what you like.
@EndNode

@Node DL_History "The History Of ConfScan_DL - © 1994 KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                      - - - ≠†≠†≠†HiSTORY ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   
   2.6.02   25-Aug-94 New         : With the '-r' option, you can now 
                                    manually remove your saved tagged
                                    files.

   2.6.01   11-Aug-94 Improved    : Now recognizes the new structure from
                                    ConfScan which is a bit smaller.

   2.6.00   07-Aug-94 New         : Better layout, not so boring anymore.

                      New         : It recognizes the new structure that
                                    ConfScan uses.

   2.5.09   06-Jun-94 Improved    : Optimized the source, this was mainly
                                    possible thanks to Joe (/X 3.38). Output
                                    is now almost 4Kb smaller!

   2.5.08   18-May-94 New         : Is now able to read the slightly different
                                    tooltypes that the Config program leaves
                                    behind.

   2.5.07   18-May-94 Fixed       : The user statistics are now saved in the
                                    ENV: dir (by ConfScan) and are now read
                                    correctly (was T:).

   2.5.06   11-Mar-94 New         : New tooltype: AREA.code where <code> is
                                    the conference access you have given an
                                    user (the F option in the user editor).
                                    it works just like USER.SLOTNUMBER, so
                                    AREA.NEW=NEVER will prevent new users
                                    from downloading. 
                                    
                                    New tooltype: AREA.FiLE=<filename>
                                    This file will be shown to users when
                                    they want to download.

   2.5.04   29-Mar-94 Improved    : After USER.SLOTNUMBER you can now enter
                                    an argument, either NEVER or ALWAYS.
                                    This way you can also grant users to
                                    have override access to all restrictions
                                    you may have put on other users. For
                                    example: USER.2=ALWAYS, user #2 shall
                                    always be able to download, no matter
                                    what the restrictions in the D.info.
                                    USER.2=NEVER means that he can NEVER
                                    download.

   2.5.02   26-Mar-94 Improved    : internal message will be shown unless
                                    you specify NODE.FiLE, CONF.FiLE or
                                    USER.FiLE in the icon. To show the in-
                                    ternal message, simply delete that
                                    tooltype entry (or put it between
                                    brackets).

                      New         : ConfScan_DL can now check for a baud-
                                    rate per node. New tooltype:
                                    BAUD.x=y - where x is node number and
                                               y the minimum baud rate
                                               (i.e. BAUD.0=9600).
                                    *Requested by Pharaoh/SR*

   2.5.01   25-Mar-94 Improved    : You can now also enter iNTERNAL after
                                    NODE.FiLE, CONF.FiLE and USER.FiLE to
                                    display an internal message instead of
                                    a file.

   2.5.00   25-Mar-94 New         : You can now exclude node's conf's and
                                    even user's from downloading. But also
                                    allow certain users to download in/on
                                    a conf/node. New tooltypes:
                                    NODE.X=NO/ACSLEVEL/FiLENAME
                                    CONF.X=NO/ACSLEVEL/FiLENAME
                                    USER.X
                                    NODE.FiLE=FiLENAME
                                    CONF.FiLE=FiLENAME
                                    USER.FiLE=FiLENAME
                                    *Requested by Chaplin&Stony/PHUN*

   2.4.00   10-Feb-94 Fixed       : Conference jumping bug fixed.

   2.3.04   13-Jan-94 Improved    : ConfScan_DL is now a separate part of
                                    the ConfScan package...
@EndNode

@Node Registration "Registration info - /X-PoWeR! - KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                    - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ REGiSTRATiON ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   ConfScan may be considered FREE-WARE.  That means that you can do with
   it  whatever you want, but DO NOT ALTER THE CODE, and YOU MAY NOT SELL
   iT!

   However,  special registered versions are available.  These version do
   not differ from the (public) available versions except that registered
   versions  notify  the user that it is in fact a registered version 8-)
   Some  sysops  asked for one, so it now is possible.  Another advantage
   is  that  you  will  most  likely  get  a  more  up to date version of
   ConfScan.   ConfScan  is  always  under  development so by registering
   yourself  you  will  get the most current version (plus updates if you
   call regularly).

                      - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ SUPPORT ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   Only  major  updates/bugfixes  (like this one) will be released to the
   masses,  however,  if you want to get updates on a regular basis (even
   little fixes) you can register yourself and ask for the updates.

   I  also  offer you support for ConfScan!  You can at Channel-X, or you
   can  contact  me  via  internet,  AND ALL FOR NOTHiNG!  Here is how to
   reach me:

                    Channel-X      ∑ +31-2290-62244
                                     +31-2290-62535

                    Last Outpost   ∑ +31-7201-57682
                                     +31-7202-01182

                    Undiscovered   ∑ +31-2294-4442
                                     +31-2294-1442

                                   Internet:
                                   ~~~~~~~~~
                         killraven@channelx.hacktic.nl


   The only thing you WiLL NEVER EVER get is a ConfScan T-shirt... ;-)

@EndNode

@Node KiLLER "KiLLER - The New Way Of Nuking! - By KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                        - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ KiLLER ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

                              YOUR DEADLY FRiEND!

   KiLLER  is the new nuker that I am currently working on.  It will be a
   totally  *NEW* way of nuking, no nuker is quite like it.  It will have
   plenty  of  options  for  the  users,  a nice layout and ofcourse fast
   performance.

   KiLLER  can act like your average every day nuker (and that is exactly
   how the currently spread versions work), but the new and coming KiLLER
   will have some neat features:

   ∑  TRS,  Total Reverse System.  As a sysop you will be able to reverse
   (undo) ANY action that has been performed with KiLLER.  KiLLER keeps a
   log  that  records  all actions performed by KiLLER.  This way you can
   easily undo any KiLLiNGS of cosysops and/or users.

   ∑  User  nuking!  Users are often the ones who tell you what files are
   fake/lame/old/etc.   So  why  not  let them place comments in the file
   directory  (dirx)?  KiLLER will let users KiLL files in the sense that
   they  can  place  a comment, but will not actually deduct credits from
   the uploader or remove the file.  When you, as sysop, start KiLLER the
   next  time you will be informed of any user KiLLiNG and you can decide
   wether this is a valid KiLLiNG or not.

   ∑ Fully GUi!  KiLLER will come with a GUi for the sysop, just like the
   Config  program  of  ConfScan!   This will make KiLLiNG as easy and as
   funny as playing BombMan!  But this will be made AFTER there is a full
   and  working version of KiLLER/Ami-Express.  So this will take a while
   (fall 94 I guess).

   ∑   Total  configuration  for  both  sysops  and  users  with  KiLLiNG
   privileges.  Every question that KiLLER will ask can be pre-configured
   so  you  can walk through KiLLER with [return]s as all default answers
   are configurable.  Quiting will also be possible from any question!

   ∑  Logfile creator for logging all uploads and/or KiLLiNGS.  This will
   speed  up  things  significantly!   At the moment KiLLER is capable of
   reading BossNuke logfile, but this will (ofcourse) change.

   ∑  File moving ANYWHERE you want.  You will be able to move files from
   ANY  dir  to  ANY  conference  in  ANY  dir,  or  copy  them  to other
   conferences.  You name it, KiLLER can do it.

              - - - ≠†≠†≠ [ WHEN WiLL iT BE READY? ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   The  new  KiLLER  will  hopefully  be  ready this year, but due to the
   enormous  extent  of the powers of KiLLER, it may well be that it will
   not   be   ready   until  next  year  (really).   But  don't  despair,
   beta-version  will  be  put  out  to  selected  sysops,  so if you are
   interested, contact your local MYSTiC board now (or contact me)!

        - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ WHAT GOOD DOES iT DO FOR ME KNOW? ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   At  this  point you have no benefit from it, asides from the fact that
   you  can  start  a nuker from ConfScan (simply call it 'Killer').  But
   ConfScan is already capable of marking files to be 'KiLLED' later on.

   In the mean time, be patient, enjoy ConfScan and take care...

@EndNode

@Node SysopCommands "Special Sysop Commands - © 1994 KiLLraVeN/MYSTiC"
                    - - - ≠†≠†≠†[ ALL COMMANDS ] ≠†≠†≠†- - -

   Here  is a brief list of ALL arguments that ConfScan recognizes.  Some
   arguments  require a certain access level, if not given, all users can
   use the arguments.


   N.B.:   The 'N' command and 'CS' command parse arguments the same way,
   so  every  example  I give for 'N' can also be applied to 'CS' (unless
   specified different).

   <date> - N 06-26-94
   ~~~~~~
   This  will  make  ConfScan  search the current conference for the date
   '06-26-94'  in  the  upload  directory.   If  there  is  no  directory
   specified, the upload dir file will be the default.

   <-x>   - N -5
   ~~~~
   ConfScan  will  search  the  current conference for the date five days
   back from TODAY.  So you can also read it as "show me the new files of
   the last 5 days." And again in the upload dir file.

   <S>    - N S
   ~~~
   This  is  the  normal  'S'  argument  (Since  last  on).  It will make
   ConfScan  search  for  the  date that the user was last on the system.
   And in the upload dir file.

   <T>    - N T
   ~~~
   The T comes from Today.  The date to search for will be set to today's
   date.   Needless  to  say this is done in the upload dir file although
   you can specify another dir file.


   <U>   - N S U
   ~~~
   The dir file to search in, is now set to the upload dir file.

   <A>   - F A or N -10 A
   ~~~
   All dir files will be taken into account when searching for a date.

   <H>   - CS H or N -5 H
   ~~~
   The hold dir file will be scanned for the given date.

   <x>   - N 5 U or F 3
   ~~~
   The  'x'  stands  for  any number and represents the number of the dir
   file that will be the target to search the date in.


   <NS>  - N S U NS or F A NS
   ~~~~
   NonStop  display  of  all  the  files,  no prompt will be given and no
   pauses between conferences.  You will be able to break it with CTRL-C.


   <+>   - CS +
   ~~~
   This  argument only works with the CS command.  If, after scanning, in
   more  than  1  conference new files were found, a small report will be
   displayed  on  screen  telling you how many bytes/files were upload in
   the conferences with new files.  If there was only ONE conference with
   new  files,  the  report  will  not be generated since you can see the
   stats in the final bar when CS exits.

   Not  every  user  can use this option, only users with Hold access (or
   higher) can do this.


   <A> or <G>  - N S G or N S A A
   ~~~~~~~~~~
   This  will  force  the  'N'  command  to  act like 'CS'.  It will make
   ConfScan  go  in  Multiple  Conference  mode.   In  other  words,  all
   conferences will be scanned for new files.


   All  of  these  arguments  can  be  combined, here are some daily used
   examples:

   CS NS +  - Scan  all dirs in all conferences for new files,  show them
              nonstop and generate a report with the upload bytes/files.

   CS T     - Scan  all  dirs in all conferences for new files,  uploaded
              today.

   CS -5 H  - What files were upload in the hold dirs the last 5 days?

   N -5 NS  - Show  me  all  files  from  the last 5 days nonstop of this
              conference (current conference).

   F A NS   - Give me all files of all dirs NonStop.

   N S G    - This is the same as 'CS', it will show you  all  new  files
              since  your  last  logon  from all upload dirs and from all
              conferences.

   N S A G  - This  is  the  same as 'CS A', it will scan all dirs in all
              conferences for new files since the last logon.
@EndNode
